The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Exide profit jumps 47%

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Ganguly: In control

 Calcutta, Oct. 21: Exide Industries Ltd has posted a 47 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 29.1 crore in the quarter ended September 30 against Rs 19.73 crore in the same period last year.

 The net turnover was Rs 338. 67 crore compared with Rs 307.09 crore, recording a rise of 11 per cent. 

 The second quarter result was taken on record at the board meeting held in Calcutta today. 

 Earnings per share (EPS) during the quarter was Rs 3.9 compared with Rs 2.8 during the corresponding period of the previous financial year, even as the capital base increased following the preferential issue of shares late last year.

 Exide executive chairman and chief executive officer S.B. Ganguly said the measures taken by the company to combat the rising lead prices like operating waste reduction, improving quality and adopting other cost-cutting exercises have resulted in improved profitability.

 The threat of rising lead prices is now contained to a large extent and the future outlook is positive. Exide continues to remain the brand of choice in all the segments of the market where we operate, he said.

 The rise in sales volumes of automotive and industrial batteries, which took a sharp upward turn during the first quarter, continued unabated. 

 During the quarter, the companys automotive battery business grew 16 per cent in volume and 18 per cent in sales revenue. The industrial battery segment also notched up impressive gains of 20 per cent in volume terms and 22 per cent in sales revenue. 




